    medications: [
      { name: "Stethoscope", type: "Assessment Tool", action: "Acoustic device used for auscultation of heart sounds (S1, S2, murmurs), lung sounds (crackles, wheezes, rhonchi), bowel sounds, and blood pressure. Bell for low-pitched sounds (S3, S4, murmurs), diaphragm for high-pitched sounds (S1, S2, breath sounds, bowel sounds)", sideEffects: "Must be cleaned between patients (infection control). Cold bell/diaphragm can cause patient discomfort: warm before use", contra: "Never auscultate through clothing: always place directly on skin for accurate assessment", pearl: "Auscultate lung sounds: anterior (6 sites), posterior (6 sites), lateral. Compare bilaterally. Listen for a full respiratory cycle at each site. Document location and character of any abnormal sounds." },
      { name: "Penlight", type: "Assessment Tool", action: "Used to assess pupillary response (direct and consensual), oral cavity inspection, and skin assessment in poorly lit areas. Pupil assessment: Shine light from lateral side into each eye, assess for brisk constriction (direct response) and constriction in opposite eye (consensual response)", sideEffects: "Bright light uncomfortable for photophobic patients or those with migraines", contra: "Use with caution in patients with eye injuries or recent eye surgery", pearl: "PERRLA documentation: Pupils Equal, Round, Reactive to Light and Accommodation. Normal pupil size: 2-6mm. Document size in mm, shape, and speed of response (brisk, sluggish, fixed). Unequal pupils (anisocoria) >1mm difference is abnormal: report immediately." }
    ],
    pearls: ["Always perform the assessment in the same systematic order to avoid missing findings: consistency prevents errors.", "Compare bilaterally: Always compare one side to the other (lung sounds, pulses, pupils, strength, sensation). Asymmetry is often more significant than individual findings.", "For abdominal assessment, remember: Inspect → Auscultate → Percuss → Palpate. Auscultate BEFORE palpation because touching the abdomen can alter bowel sounds.", "Document using approved terminology: 'Lungs CTA bilaterally' (clear to auscultation), 'Abdomen NTND' (non-tender, non-distended), 'A&Ox4' (alert and oriented to person, place, time, situation).", "Cluster assessments: Perform all interventions during one visit to minimize patient disruption and maximize rest periods. However, never rush an assessment: thoroughness prevents missed findings."],
    lifespan: { title: "Across the Lifespan", content: "Pediatric: Assess fontanelles in infants (bulging = increased ICP, sunken = dehydration). Use pediatric-specific vital sign ranges. Perform assessment in parent's lap for toddlers. Leave invasive assessments (ears, throat) for last.\n\nElderly: Allow extra time. Assess for fall risk, skin breakdown (check bony prominences), cognitive changes. Distinguish acute confusion (delirium) from chronic (dementia). Medications may mask normal assessment findings." },
    quiz: [{ question: "When performing an abdominal assessment, what is the correct sequence of techniques?", options: ["Inspect → Palpate → Percuss → Auscultate", "Inspect → Auscultate → Percuss → Palpate", "Auscultate → Inspect → Palpate → Percuss", "Percuss → Palpate → Inspect → Auscultate"], correct: 1, rationale: "For the abdomen ONLY, the correct order is Inspect → Auscultate → Percuss → Palpate. Auscultation is performed BEFORE percussion and palpation because touching or tapping the abdomen can stimulate peristalsis and alter bowel sounds, producing false results. For all other body systems, the standard sequence is Inspect → Palpate → Percuss → Auscultate." }]
